Investigating Ways to Efficiently Foster Healthy Learning Environments in Schools

Project 1¶

1.1 Introduction¶

In the United States, many high school students take a standardized test when applying to college, one of which is the SAT. The scores range from 600 to 2400, with a higher score being more desirable. The SAT is one of the most critical factors in college admissions. This study aims to investigate school traits that may contribute to student health and explore non-academic methods to enhance SAT score performance in under performing schools.

Unlike typical public high schools, NYC public high schools have admissions processes that permit them to shape their incoming student body, as opposed to traditional high schools where the intake is determined by local middle school zoning. Variations in school environments could potentially improve mental and physical health, which may positively influence SAT scores. This research is inspired by listening to health and habit podcasts, particularly by Stanford neuroscientist Andrew Huberman. This study will focus on school characteristics that may passively implement some of Huberman's suggestions to observe if SAT scores are affected. The goal is to find and discuss some passive and economically efficient strategies that schools can implement to improve the educational and academic achievement of their students.

Huberman's podcast emphasizes the significant mood enhancements from morning sunlight exposure. As the quality of morning light varies with wake-up times, influenced by school start times, this factor could conceivably impact SAT performance. Blume, C., Garbazza, C., \& Spitschan, M. (2019) discuss the critical effects of light on human circadian rhythms, sleep, and mood, highlighting light's potential impact on academic success. This study seeks to identify an optimal start time that could bolster student performance by leveraging the natural benefits of morning light. Studies by Song, C., Ikei, H., \& Miyazaki, Y. (2016), and Kuo, F. E., \& Taylor, A. F. (2004), present evidence of improved performance with exposure to nature. Purtell, K. M., \& Gershoff, E. T. (2015) found that fiber consumption enhances teen performance. Lau, Y. (2022) provides evidence of the benefits of diversity, which will be examined using an HHI diversity score which will be talked about in depth later. Berding, K., Carbia, C., \& Cryan, J. F. (2021) also report the advantages of fiber intake. I can measure fiber intake by the number of salad bars per lunch served. Finally, Bayar, A., \& Karaduman, H. A. (2021) conclude that extracurricular activities boost academic success. Larger schools have the resources and student population to support numerous clubs and extracurricular activities. However, (Ramchander and Naude 2018) fail to draw the same conclusion in a university study that took place in South Africa. Taken together, these studies propose approaches to improve student performance, indicating that modifications to school environments and incorporating factors that enhance student well-being could be advantageous.

Overall the papers are in studies of controlled environments. The difference in my research is that it is directly talking about high schools and student achievement through SAT scores. We are looking at real life applications here.

I will use datasets sourced from New York City's 2015 Street Tree Census, school food reports, and fast-food restaurant data. Based on the literature reviewed, it is believed that slight improvements in SAT scores should be observed in schools with more salad bars, more trees, and fewer fast-food restaurants nearby.

The overall findings of my research suggest that the anticipated health-improving factors did not yield the expected outcomes. However, diversity, larger school enrollments, and earlier start times do seem to play a positive, significant role in academic achievement. In our analysis, we will start by looking at the data, followed by initial findings and, lastly, our regression results.

def to_numeric_if_string(df, column):
    if df[column].dtype == 'object':
        df[column] = pd.to_numeric(df[column].str.replace('%', ''), errors='coerce') / 100
    elif df[column].dtype in ['float64', 'int64']:
        df[column] = df[column] / 100
        
scores_df['Percent Tested'] = scores_df['Percent Tested'].str.replace('%', '').astype(float) *100
# Calculate the 'School Day Length' in hours
# Define a function to convert time to datetime, handling NaN values
def convert_time(time_series):
    return pd.to_datetime(time_series, format='%I:%M %p', errors='coerce')

# Apply the function to the 'Start Time' and 'End Time' columns
scores_df['Start Time'] = convert_time(scores_df['Start Time'])
scores_df['End Time'] = convert_time(scores_df['End Time'])

# Calculate 'School Day Length' in hours, while handling NaN values
scores_df['School Day Length'] = (scores_df['End Time'] - scores_df['Start Time']).dt.total_seconds() / 3600

# Show the result and any NaNs in 'School Day Length'
scores_df[['Start Time', 'End Time', 'School Day Length']].head()

scores_df['Start Time Hour'] = scores_df['Start Time'].dt.hour + scores_df['Start Time'].dt.minute / 60
scores_df['End Time Hour'] = scores_df['End Time'].dt.hour + scores_df['End Time'].dt.minute / 60

# Cleaning the data
# Dropping the rows <= 0 values for 'School Day Length'
scores_df = scores_df[scores_df['School Day Length'] > 0]
scores_df = scores_df.dropna(subset=['Average Score (SAT Math)', 'Average Score (SAT Reading)', 'Average Score (SAT Writing)'])


# Calculate the total SAT score
scores_df['Average Total SAT Score'] = scores_df['Average Score (SAT Math)'] + scores_df['Average Score (SAT Reading)'] + scores_df['Average Score (SAT Writing)']  


def calculate_range(series):
    return series.max() - series.min()



percent_columns = ['Percent White', 'Percent Black', 'Percent Hispanic', 'Percent Asian', 'Percent Tested']
for col in percent_columns:
    to_numeric_if_string(scores_df, col)

def hhi(row):
    values = [row['Percent White'], row['Percent Black'], row['Percent Hispanic'], row['Percent Asian']]
    return sum((x**2) for x in values if pd.notnull(x))

scores_df['HHI'] = scores_df.apply(hhi, axis=1) * 10

def to_24hr_time(decimal_hour):
    hours = int(decimal_hour)
    minutes = int((decimal_hour - hours) * 60)
    return f'{str(hours).zfill(2)}:{str(minutes).zfill(2)}'

# Apply the function to the 'Start Time Hour' column
scores_df['Start Time Hours'] = scores_df['Start Time Hour'].apply(to_24hr_time)

For data cleaning, I have deleted rows with missing SAT scores as that is the Y value which is central to the question.

To measure the time per day spent in school, a 'School day length' column was created by subtracting the start time from the end time of the schools.

To interpret the summary table: "Mean" refers to the average value, "Min" stands for the minimum value, and "Max" represents the maximum value. "Std" indicates the standard deviation, which measures the spread of the data around the mean. The interquartile range (IQR) is the difference between the 25th (lower quartile) and 75th percentiles (upper quartile), showing the middle 50% of the data. "Range" is the difference between the max and min values. The "50%" value is the median, or the midpoint of the data.

The summary statistics reveal that after data cleaning, we are working with 374 schools, a relatively small sample. The average SAT score of 1275.35 points to moderate to high performance across these schools, with a significant standard deviation of 194.87 indicating wide variability in scores. Aside from "School Day Length," the large standard deviations and interquartile across our variables suggest diverse data rather than concentration within narrow ranges. "School Day Length" averages slightly over 7 hours, but the range shows notable differences in school day durations. HHI scores have a decent interquartile range and a standard deviation of 1.6, which is a good characteristic to warrant exploration of the variable. I have made the diversity score out of 10 instead of decimals for clarity. Start Time Hour is an interesting variable too. I can see that most schools start between 8AM and 8:30 am. The standard deviation sugests that we cna explore further than the interquartile range. Student enrollment values were less than I expected, so there are many schools that are around 500 in size. However, with a large standard deviation of 774, there seems to be a good number of schools that are much larger than the average. Overall, these summary statistics show that the data looks promising for deeper analysis with these X-values.

bins = pd.cut(scores_df['HHI'], bins=15)
# Create range labels for each bin
bin_ranges = [f"{round(bin_.left, 2)}-{round(bin_.right, 2)}" for bin_ in bins.cat.categories]

# Map the HHI values to the bin ranges for plotting
scores_df['HHI Bin Range'] = pd.cut(scores_df['HHI'], bins=bins.cat.categories, labels=bin_ranges)

# Group by the bin ranges to get the average SAT scores
grouped = scores_df.groupby('HHI Bin Range')['Average Total SAT Score'].mean().reset_index()

# Fit a 4th degree polynomial to the binned data
coefs = np.polyfit(range(len(grouped)), grouped['Average Total SAT Score'], 4)
poly = np.poly1d(coefs)

# Generate a sequence of x values for plotting the trend line
x_trend = np.linspace(0, len(grouped) - 1, 100)

# Calculate the y values from the polynomial trend line
y_trend = poly(x_trend)

# Plot the bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
barplot = sns.barplot(x='HHI Bin Range', y='Average Total SAT Score', data=grouped, color='pink')

# Plotting the polynomial trend line onto the bar plot
plt.plot(x_trend, y_trend, color='red', label='4th Degree Polynomial Trend Line')

# Set plot labels and title
plt.xlabel('Diversity Score Range (lower is more diverse)')
plt.ylabel('Average SAT Score')
plt.title('Average SAT Scores by HHI Bins with Polynomial Trend Line')
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(ticks=np.arange(len(grouped)), labels=grouped['HHI Bin Range'], rotation=45)
ax = plt.gca()
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Here we have a bar plot and a third defree polynomical trendline. There seems to be a trend where more diverse schools tend to have a higher average SAT score. import geopandas as gpd
school_counts = scores_df.groupby('Zip Code')['School ID'].nunique().reset_index(name='Schools per Zip Code')
scores_df = scores_df.merge(school_counts, on='Zip Code', how='left')
zip_codes_gdf = gpd.read_file("http://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/GENZ2014/shp/cb_2014_us_zcta510_500k.zip")
nyc_zip_code_prefixes = ('100', '101', '102', '103', '104', '110', '111', '112', '113', '114', '116')
nyc_zip_codes_gdf = zip_codes_gdf[zip_codes_gdf['GEOID10'].str.startswith(nyc_zip_code_prefixes)]
# Calculate average SAT scores (Math, Reading, Writing) for each zip code
average_scores_by_zip = scores_df.groupby('Zip Code')['Schools per Zip Code'].mean().reset_index()
nyc_zip_codes_gdf = zip_codes_gdf[zip_codes_gdf['GEOID10'].str.startswith(nyc_zip_code_prefixes)]
# Merge the average scores data with the geographic data
average_scores_by_zip['Zip Code'] = average_scores_by_zip['Zip Code'].astype(str)
nyc_zip_codes_scores_gdf = nyc_zip_codes_gdf.merge(average_scores_by_zip, left_on='GEOID10', right_on='Zip Code', how='left')
nyc_zip_codes_scores_gdf = nyc_zip_codes_scores_gdf.set_geometry('geometry')
# Set up the figure and axis
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
# Plot the zip codes
nyc_zip_codes_scores_gdf.plot(ax=ax, color= 'lightgrey', edgecolor='black')

# Plot the average scores, using a colormap
nyc_zip_codes_scores_gdf.dropna(subset=['Schools per Zip Code']).plot(
    ax=ax,
    column='Schools per Zip Code', # Column to base the colors on
    cmap='Reds', # Colormap for different average scores
    legend=True, # To show a color bar legend
    legend_kwds={'label': "Schools per Zip Code"}, # Legend label
    missing_kwds={'color': 'lightgrey'},# Color for missing values  
)

ax.axis('off')
ax.set_axis_off()
ax.set_title('Schools per Zip Code in New York City')
# Show the map
plt.show()

The map provides a visual representation of the distribution of schools across various zip codes in New York City. A significant number of zip codes contain at least one school. This indicates that characteristics of zip codes could be analyzed to understand the impact of a school's environment on SAT scores.

This map displays the average school start time by ZIP code. There is significant variation within neighboring areas, but one interesting observation is that some areas like Lower Brooklyn, Eastern Queens, and Manhattan, which had higher SAT scores, had school start times later in the morning, closer to 8:30. Conversely, the Band in Northern Brooklyn and Western Queens, characterized by lower SAT scores, had start times closer to 8 AM. This observation is contrary to what we might expect based on an earlier graph I created, where schools that started earlier, at 8 AM, tended to have higher scores than those that started later. Also, note that on any given day, all locations will experience sunrise within two minutes of each other, which is negligible compared to the roughly 45-minute to 1-hour difference in school start times we see here.

Project 3¶

3.1 Potential Data to Scrape¶

From Project 2, I gained a greater understanding of what may affect the average SAT score beyond the amount of preparation time. However, I have found some datasets with the locations of trees and fast food restaurants. To analyze this data, I found two datasets to scrape: one for population per zipcode and the other for land area per zipcode. I can use these to analyze the densities of trees and restaurants among other x variables. This will allow us to gain a deeper understanding of how x-variables affect SAT scores and, hopefully, we can establish some causality.

3.2 Potential Challenges¶

Challenges in web scraping can range from encountering paywalls for access to information, facing restrictions imposed by websites against data extraction, to the sheer volume of data that could make the scraping process excessively time-consuming. Furtheremore some data can be incomplete for my data set and therefore will resut in me dropping values.

In my case, after extensie searching, the required data was readily accessible for scraping, and I fortunately did not encounter many of the aforementioned obstacles except for finding data of NYC zip code size as and I could only find data for Manhatten Island and none from the other four bourghs. This is an issue becuase my data set on NYC highschools is already very small at less than 400 schools. I want keep all schools avalible to analyse.

        # Append the array of data to the DataFrame

Machine Learning¶

Using machine learning we should be able to improove out models obtianed from regressions. Our objective function is as follows $$ \min_{j,s} \left[ \sum_{i: x_{i,j} \leq s, x_i \in R1} (AS_i - \hat{AS}_{R1})^2 + \sum_{i: x_{i,j} > s, x_i \in R2} (AS_i - \hat{AS}_{R2})^2 \right] $$ where AS is a school's average Sat Score, and i and j are the indexes.

We also want to minimise the sum of the following which is the squared distances of the observed and the model. $$ (AS_i - \hat{AS}_{R1})^2 \quad \text{and} \quad (AS_i - \hat{AS}_{R2})^2 $$

A good prediction will minimise the sum the squared errors.

In the above importance matrix, we see that the individual races matter more than overall diversity. This does point to the notion that there is a difference in performance across races, similar to what was seen in the regression table studying HHI. However, the HHI diversity score variable also has high importance, which suggests that diversity may mitigate inequality. Meanwhile, the variables looking at health, such as restaurants per 10,000 people and salad bars, saw very low importance in predicting SAT scores. It is important to note that these health variables have higher exposure to confounders than the variables coming from the primary scores dataset.

Conclusion¶

All in all, we have uncovered some interesting insights on schools and their SAT scores. Most notably, racial diversity, school scheduals, and various health inducing variables were studied.

The variables measuring school start time, total school time, diversity, and enrollment were derived directly frojm the scores data set. Many of the results from project one and project two were suprising. Finally in the regression and machine learnign sections, the suprising results were shown to be significant.

Moreover, the five merged datasets added to this project that are thought to have health inducing effects have provided limited insights into the correlation between healthy lifestyles and SAT scores. It is predicted that this may be due to underlying confounding variables whcih we dont ahve the tools to control for. The next issue that we have is the extremely limited data set available. There are more health variables worth looking into available for merging and analysis, especially from https://www.schools.nyc.gov.

All in all, the evidence is insufficient to support policy changes in schools aimed at promoting physical health. However, there is evidence suggesting that a shift towards fewer schools, but with larger and more diverse student bodies that offer more clubs and extracurricular activities, could be beneficial. Data on urban tree density appears promising if givin more data, supporting the notion that tree planting in densely populated urban areas may offer the greatest marginal benefits to the student community network.

In the future, I hope to use more datapoints. If there is more data on schools from other cities and after controlling for city fixed effects, I may be able to get stronger results for the passive variabels that affect health. My goal is to improve the education experience by improving school enviorments that will maximise the utility from learning. There is the old saying "work smarter and not harder" and I will reasearch if these benefits from these heath variables could subsitute mental health counseling which costs money, time, and labour whilest not always being effective.
